WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.800
Hi, I'm Sarah Altman, a Data Science Educator at Posit.

00:00:03.800 --> 00:00:06.600
In this video, I'll show you how to create your first Python

00:00:06.600 --> 00:00:09.000
project in Positron.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:11.360
I'll walk through the process of opening a folder,

00:00:11.360 --> 00:00:13.360
setting up a virtual environment,

00:00:13.360 --> 00:00:16.120
creating a Quarto document, versioning with Git,

00:00:16.120 --> 00:00:19.639
and deploying Deposit Connect.

00:00:19.639 --> 00:00:22.360
First, make sure you've downloaded Positron

00:00:22.360 --> 00:00:24.760
and have a supported Python interpreter installed.

00:00:24.760 --> 00:00:26.480
Let's create our project.

00:00:26.480 --> 00:00:29.480
The first step is to open a folder.

00:00:29.520 --> 00:00:33.200
This will create a workspace for our project.

00:00:33.200 --> 00:00:36.840
I'll choose New Folder and then Python Project,

00:00:36.840 --> 00:00:38.919
and then pick a name for the folder.

00:00:38.919 --> 00:00:41.560
I'm going to call it First Python Project

00:00:41.560 --> 00:00:45.959
and select a location by clicking Browse.

00:00:45.959 --> 00:00:48.799
And then I'm going to check Initialize Git Repository

00:00:48.799 --> 00:00:52.080
to set up version control for the project.

00:00:52.080 --> 00:00:55.639
If you don't plan on using Git, you can skip this step.

00:00:55.639 --> 00:00:59.279
Next, I'm going to set up the virtual environment.

00:01:00.080 --> 00:01:03.279
Make sure Create a New Virtual Environment is selected

00:01:03.279 --> 00:01:06.879
and then select a way to create the virtual environment.

00:01:06.879 --> 00:01:09.680
You can either use Venv, UV, or Conda

00:01:09.680 --> 00:01:12.599
if you have UV and Conda installed.

00:01:12.599 --> 00:01:15.080
I'm going to use Venv.

00:01:15.080 --> 00:01:18.040
Then finally, select a Python interpreter.

00:01:18.040 --> 00:01:20.040
This is the version of Python that you

00:01:20.040 --> 00:01:21.959
want to use in your project.

00:01:21.959 --> 00:01:22.959
And click Create.

00:01:23.680 --> 00:01:26.519
Now, Positron has opened our new folder.

00:01:26.519 --> 00:01:28.800
You can see the files that it created over here

00:01:28.800 --> 00:01:32.559
in the File Explorer on the left-hand side.

00:01:32.559 --> 00:01:34.639
Positron also created and activated

00:01:34.639 --> 00:01:36.559
that virtual environment.

00:01:36.559 --> 00:01:38.959
This means that much of the setup for our Python project

00:01:38.959 --> 00:01:41.279
is already done.

00:01:41.279 --> 00:01:43.160
Now that the virtual environment is active,

00:01:43.160 --> 00:01:46.720
we can install the libraries that we'll need for our project.

00:01:46.720 --> 00:01:48.160
We're going to open the terminal,

00:01:48.160 --> 00:01:50.959
and then we're going to install the Python library.

00:01:51.879 --> 00:01:53.720
We're going to open the terminal,

00:01:53.720 --> 00:01:56.320
and then install Jupyter, Pandas, and Matplotlib.

00:02:02.160 --> 00:02:04.480
We'll need Jupyter to render Cordo documents.

00:02:08.559 --> 00:02:11.000
Next, I'll capture the environment

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:14.360
in a requirements.txt file so it's reproducible.

00:02:21.720 --> 00:02:24.759
Positron can recognize requirements.txt files

00:02:24.759 --> 00:02:27.960
in a project and can prompt the user to install libraries

00:02:27.960 --> 00:02:30.360
from the file, which makes it easy for others

00:02:30.360 --> 00:02:33.800
to recreate the same environment.

00:02:33.800 --> 00:02:35.720
Now that our environment is ready,

00:02:35.720 --> 00:02:38.479
we can start adding files and running Python code.

00:02:38.479 --> 00:02:41.600
I'm going to do my work in a Cordo document.

00:02:41.600 --> 00:02:47.520
I'll first pull up the Command Palette with Command-Shift-P.

00:02:47.520 --> 00:02:49.559
You can access all of Positron's files

00:02:49.720 --> 00:02:51.759
You can access all of Positron's commands

00:02:51.759 --> 00:02:54.759
from the Command Palette.

00:02:54.759 --> 00:02:57.279
And then I'm going to search for Cordo new document.

00:03:00.080 --> 00:03:03.039
Now I have a new blank Cordo document.

00:03:03.039 --> 00:03:06.720
So let's load some data and take a look at it.

00:03:06.720 --> 00:03:11.360
First, I'll insert a new Python cell into the Cordo doc.

00:03:11.360 --> 00:03:15.080
And now I'm going to read in some weekly US gasoline prices

00:03:15.080 --> 00:03:16.399
data from Tidy Tuesday.

00:03:20.559 --> 00:03:22.839
This code imports some libraries and then

00:03:22.839 --> 00:03:25.679
reads the data in from a URL.

00:03:25.679 --> 00:03:29.559
After running this code, notice that df and the other variables

00:03:29.559 --> 00:03:31.479
we created show up in the Variables pane

00:03:31.479 --> 00:03:33.240
over on the right-hand side.

00:03:33.240 --> 00:03:36.440
I can click this spreadsheet icon next to df

00:03:36.440 --> 00:03:39.320
to launch the Data Explorer, a spreadsheet-style view where

00:03:39.320 --> 00:03:41.759
you can sort, filter, and view summary statistics

00:03:41.759 --> 00:03:45.600
for your data, all without writing any additional code.

00:03:45.600 --> 00:03:47.559
Now let's visualize the data.

00:03:47.559 --> 00:03:48.559
So let's run that code.

00:03:50.960 --> 00:03:54.639
Now you'll notice that the plot shows up over in the Plots

00:03:54.639 --> 00:03:57.759
pane on the right.

00:03:57.759 --> 00:04:00.119
So this is a pretty short analysis,

00:04:00.119 --> 00:04:01.880
but it's a good starting point.

00:04:01.880 --> 00:04:04.360
And now we can render our Cordo document

00:04:04.360 --> 00:04:05.960
to see what it looks like.

00:04:05.960 --> 00:04:12.119
First, I'm going to give it a title and save the file.

00:04:18.559 --> 00:04:20.480
And now I can click Preview to render.

00:04:29.920 --> 00:04:33.920
The rendered result opens in the Viewer pane on the right.

00:04:33.920 --> 00:04:37.839
Next, I'm going to commit and push my changes to GitHub.

00:04:37.839 --> 00:04:39.720
This is the source control view where

00:04:39.720 --> 00:04:43.040
you can stage changes, commit, and push changes to GitHub.

00:04:43.040 --> 00:04:47.440
Click the plus next to a file to stage the changes.

00:04:48.320 --> 00:04:52.000
I'm going to add the Cordo document, the gitignore file,

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:57.040
readme, and the requirements file for now.

00:04:57.040 --> 00:05:00.320
Then I'm going to add a commit message to this message text

00:05:00.320 --> 00:05:06.720
box and click Commit.

00:05:06.720 --> 00:05:09.359
Next, I'm going to click this little cloud icon

00:05:09.359 --> 00:05:12.119
to publish the branch.

00:05:12.119 --> 00:05:14.720
This is going to create a corresponding remote

00:05:14.720 --> 00:05:18.239
repository on GitHub and then push the changes.

00:05:18.239 --> 00:05:21.760
So let's make a public repo.

00:05:21.760 --> 00:05:23.359
Just need to name it something else.

00:05:28.640 --> 00:05:31.640
And now Positron will create that repository

00:05:31.640 --> 00:05:33.760
and push my changes.

00:05:33.760 --> 00:05:35.040
So let's open it on GitHub.

00:05:35.040 --> 00:05:36.399
OK, here it is.

00:05:38.920 --> 00:05:41.760
The final step is to set up a deployment deposit connect

00:05:41.760 --> 00:05:44.160
so I can share my report with others.

00:05:45.160 --> 00:05:47.200
If you have access to PositConnect,

00:05:47.200 --> 00:05:49.959
you can use Posit Publisher from Positron

00:05:49.959 --> 00:05:53.440
to deploy your work to Connect.

00:05:53.440 --> 00:05:55.839
If you don't have access to PositConnect,

00:05:55.839 --> 00:05:58.160
PositConnect Cloud provides an easy way

00:05:58.160 --> 00:06:00.760
to publish quarter reports, shiny apps, and more

00:06:00.760 --> 00:06:02.119
from GitHub for free.

00:06:04.839 --> 00:06:07.119
So this is the Posit Publisher view.

00:06:07.119 --> 00:06:09.399
And I'm going to use this to create a new deployment.

00:06:09.519 --> 00:06:11.200
I click here.

00:06:11.200 --> 00:06:18.399
And then I want to deploy this gathprices.qnd file, add a name,

00:06:18.399 --> 00:06:20.519
and then select where I want to deploy it to.

00:06:23.679 --> 00:06:25.920
And then I just need to click this Deploy Your Project

00:06:25.920 --> 00:06:27.880
button, and Positron will deploy my content.

00:06:28.480 --> 00:06:31.320
OK, here's the file deployed to PositConnect.

00:06:31.320 --> 00:06:32.880
If you've been following along, you now

00:06:32.880 --> 00:06:36.839
have a basic working Python project set up in Positron,

00:06:36.839 --> 00:06:39.440
the virtual environment, version control,

00:06:39.440 --> 00:06:40.799
and it's deployment ready to go.

00:06:40.799 --> 00:06:43.440
To learn more, take a look at the corresponding blog post

00:06:43.440 --> 00:06:45.200
and the links in the description.

00:06:45.200 --> 00:06:46.600
And that's it for this video.

00:06:46.600 --> 00:06:49.000
If you have any questions, please feel free to reach out

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:51.160
to me on Twitter, Instagram, or LinkedIn.

00:06:51.160 --> 00:06:52.720
And I'll see you in the next video.

00:06:52.720 --> 00:06:53.239
Bye.

